First of all OP, there's no such thing as no error message, you're simply not looking in the right place, or in this case probably using a garbage video player.

All the people in this thread is fucking drooling over a video of a random and want you to upload the video at all costs.

First you want to get a good video player that might give you an actual error, mpv would be my go to, but probably VLC too might work.

Make sure to play the video using a terminal, so that way you'll see the error right there, for mpv you just do something like mpv video.wmv on a terminal and once the player stops it 100% will show something in the terminal.

Lastly, ffmpeg doesn't really require any coding knowledge at all, if anything you need to know more about video, codecs and shit.

ffmpeg is probably the only way you're gonna be able to do this in a private way, just look on the internet some tutorial on how to fix a corrupt video or so first and try that.

Your last resource would be reencoding the video, I'd suggest H.264 for the codec, even then it'd still take a long time to do, we are talking about hours definitely.

A command like this could encode the video to H.264

ffmpeg -i video.wmv -preset slower -crf 18 -c:v libx264 -c:a copy output-video.mp4
